elements.2211.03306_21f1891cbaeb249cafda094394031: In this paper, we introduce a novel optimization model for dense subgraph discovery in multilayer networks.
elements.2211.03306_ffa750ad683c66bc8052b5b13a806: Given an edge-weighted multilayer network, our model aims to find a vertex subset that is dense for the layer selected by an adversary
elements.2211.03306_876d5e95ca3ba2b426bc30e612bfd: Specifically, we employ a stochastic solution, i.e., a probability distribution over the family of vertex subsets, while existing work focuses only on a deterministic solution, i.e., a single vertex subset.
elements.2211.03306_e42934d172aa7bc6ec24a54dea70b: More precisely, we stochastically choose a vertex subset according to a stochastic solution and then, knowing only the stochastic solution but not a realization, the adversary selects the worst layer for us.
elements.2211.03306_7a4cf202bc323a4d072eb96b497c6: Note that the worst layer with respect to each realization of the stochastic solution may be different from that with respect to the stochastic solution.
elements.2211.03306_199947dc7d86ef760733405650530: It is worth mentioning that our model can be seen as a zero-sum two-player Stackelberg game
elements.2211.03306_5aac18e1331ea5c233318b2760a85: , where the leader is our algorithm and the follower is the adversary.

elements.2211.03306_f79cd6095fbd3e1eed3fe86e0ae11: We evaluate the performance of a stochastic solution (or an algorithm) using the following three metrics for the layer selected by the adversary: (i) the

elements.2211.03306_6f063e063b9e782c6a9e229051ecc: , i.e., the ratio of the expected density to the optimal density, and
elements.2211.03306_18ae6f39819152757fed808a32a4c: , i.e., the difference between the optimal density and the expected density.
elements.2211.03306_58e3465473a628076886c172713ba: Therefore, we address three optimization problems according to the metrics.
elements.2211.03306_3ab17bbaa2ba650dc402ea2a38d86: Our main algorithmic contribution is to design a polynomial-time exact algorithm for our optimization model, which is applicable to all of the above three metrics
elements.2211.03306_778b23dd3056ecf0f12460a120e6b: Specifically, the algorithm first solves an LP, which is a generalization of the LP used for the densest common subgraph problem
elements.2211.03306_0ac2232e15485a60dfe12f61cfb22: and then computes an optimal probability distribution based on the LP's optimal solution.
elements.2211.03306_c7b90ba7c3419efd591458a3db0bf: We observe that the output of our algorithm has a useful structure; the family of the vertex subsets with positive probabilities has a hierarchical structure
elements.2211.03306_1101d833e9e773b7f4d96b5b3d656: This leads to several practical benefits, e.g., the largest size subset contains all the other subsets and the optimal solution obtained by our algorithm has support size at most the number of vertices (although a solution of our optimization model may have support size exponential in the number of vertices)
elements.2211.03306_a2380d83c1eb9a476e0004b43280e: Moreover, we can demonstrate that the support size of the solution obtained is upper bounded by the number of layers
elements.2211.03306_fc4f096fb2a482562b20c0626fdc7: It is desirable to have a small support size for the understandability of stochastic solutions and for purposes of simple verification and validation
elements.2211.03306_1d4097de14609316e01243ea57b3f: For practical use of our proposed algorithm, we wish to speed up our algorithm so that it is applicable to larger-scale multilayer networks.
elements.2211.03306_69b32a57b1312eab7306ae8479533: The bottleneck is the computation cost of the LP, which has a lot of variables and constraints
elements.2211.03306_7d29eda81d03765891f5f2be1ca21: To this end, we devise a simple, scalable preprocessing algorithm, which often reduces the size of the input networks significantly and results in a substantial speed-up
elements.2211.03306_4130486b79e5cac6946afd55c40f6: Specifically, the algorithm first computes an approximate solution by solving a much smaller LP than the aforementioned LP and then removes vertices from the original network using the information of the approximate solution obtained.
elements.2211.03306_dd920ea1cbb33087060bd15720dbb: Note that our preprocessing algorithm is a generalization of that proposed by Balalau et al.
elements.2211.03306_a0372e8857281c138ccf8ee8edf55: However, to verify that the preprocessing algorithm does not harm any optimal solution, we need a more sophisticated analysis, which is totally different from theirs
elements.2211.03306_7ffdb91b05227f474c431835ceae8: Finally, we conduct thorough computational experiments using synthetic graphs and real-world networks to verify the validity of our model and to evaluate the performance of our algorithms

elements.2211.03306_dab0c221b1885bac0b251677ba6ec: We introduce a novel optimization model for dense subgraph discovery in multilayer networks;

elements.2211.03306_0a18092392f8763d42eca1116102d: We devise a simple, scalable preprocessing algorithm, enabling us to apply our exact algorithm to large-scale multilayer networks in practice;
